									<p>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
										Viewed 78 times<br>
									</span>

												</td>

						<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#0C142B" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
			<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; " >
												<DIV></DIV>
<DIV>I'm not going to reply to every response posted here, but, let me generalize a few things.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>First off the demand for bards in MA &amp; DPS groups is an effect of inertia.&nbsp; At some point, the songs we used had a significant effect on modifying those groups.&nbsp; That belief still exists.&nbsp; </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>This effect is similar to guilds who only use monks to pull.&nbsp; Monks were known as pullers and rather than realizing the benefits of putting bards and sks in pull groups, they continue with their existing plan becuase they don't know better.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The "force-modifiers" between bards who are in elemental guilds and those who are in end game GoD guilds are the same.&nbsp; The difference is that thier surroundings have changed significantly.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>There are 2 types of "force-modifiers" that we provide:</DIV>
<DIV>1. Hard coded fixed numeric improvements, such as regen, attack, AC and resists.&nbsp; These modifiers are extremely useful for elemental guilds becuase they provided significant increases relative to abilities of the classes being modified.&nbsp; Those numbers havent changed for GoD and the relative improvement (especially based on softcaps) provide much less modification.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Yes, we still provide a service, but the service is not as useful.&nbsp; This is why the Evraj series of songs isn't used in high end.&nbsp; Everyone is hitting max haste, so it is useless.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>2. Percentage based increases scale better if your surrondings don't change.&nbsp; But, the surroundings have changed and percentage increase we provide have becomes less significant.&nbsp; An example: If you don't have any focus items, a 25% focus song will increase your DPS output by 25%.&nbsp; If you have 45% focus items, a 25% focus song will increase your DPS by 17%.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>You have a group of 4 wizards and a healer.&nbsp; The raid has 1 spot left (already has 2 bards in the raid) and there's another bard and wizard wanting to get into the raid.&nbsp; Adding the bard to the wizard group adds significantly less DPS than adding a wizard (endgame) while adding a bard to an elemental raid adds equal DPS.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Although percentage based modifier scales better than a fixed number modifier;&nbsp; they lose thier value when items exist that have the same functionality.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>---</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>PoP bard enhancements were at the right place.&nbsp; The amount of GoD bard enhancement is very much less than PoP.&nbsp; As more people (raid leaders) realize this, the desirability of bards falls greatly.&nbsp; Especially for raids where numbers are capped.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>You can always find a job for all bards on your raids and keep them busy.&nbsp; But after adding 2 bards, it starts to make more sense to add warriors, healers and DPS rather than another buffing class (especially becuase the gains are so much less).</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>The trend is moving towards removing the bards from the MA group and adding a second healer (usually a cleric for divine arbitration) to help make tank transitions smoother.&nbsp; That is how insignificant our roles are becoming.</DIV>
																																		<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 100; overflow: hidden;">
														<p><i>- <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=22184">Tremelo</a>  <br><font color="FF00FF">Bard Class Correspondent</font></i>
							</div>
																
										</td></tr>
